^-{ GENERAL DEFENSIVE TECHNIQUE}
^-|
cp||
fp|2|
at|
^d @e@2On partner's opening lead, your first obligation is to show attitude.  However, if it is @E@3 obvious  that attitude does not apply  you should give count. For example, pard leads the A, and board has QJxx -- then you give count. Playing standard, you play low from 3 (or 5), high from doubleton and  2nd highest from 4.

Anyway, if attitude makes no sense, you show count. Using our example, pard leads A from AK, and QJxx on board, if you show doubleton, pard will now would judge whether it makes sense to give you a ruff or not.

Next, When playing 3rd hand high, it is imperative that you play the lowest card of a sequence. So if pard leads suit, and you have QJ10, you must play the 10. If you play the Q, pard will assume you don't have the J. Let me expand a little further.  Say there is 10 on dummy, pard leads that suit, and you have QJ9, you should play the 9. Now, a slightly more complicated example. Assume partner leads low, presumably showing an honor.  Dummy has, say Jxx, and you have K10x. Normally, you should play the 10.








