^d @e@2When you lead back partner's suit, you should lead back your "remaining count." So, @E@3 let us say partner led a suit and you started with 3. Say board wins first trick, and you get in a little later. You now have two left in partner's suit.  So, assuming you play standard count, you should lead back the higher of your two remaining cards, to show that you have a doubleton remaining. If you started with 4, and have 3 left, you lead back low. This applies to both in suit and in no trump.

Let me be a bit more specific. Say partner overcalled a suit, so you know she has 5. Partner leads the suit and you have 4 and dummy has a doubleton left. If you lead back low, partner knows you started with 4, so both declarer and dummy started with 2. Therefore, leading the suit a third time will give declarer a ruff and sluff. Granted, sometimes leading back remaining count does not matter, but if you get in the habit, partner will trust you when it does matter.

Now, let us play our first Board.







